  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international efforts to address financial crimes\n- Limited regulatory framework\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence standards\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stricter regulations on financial transactions\n- Enhanced terrorist financing prevention\n- Expanded reporting and monitoring mechanisms\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Advanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Comprehensive Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Cryptocurrency transaction regulations\n\n5. Global Compliance Standards\n- Continuous updates to FATF recommendations\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n- Standardized anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Emerging Technologies\n- Artificial intelligence in transaction monitoring\n- Blockchain tracking capabilities\n- Enhanced digital forensic tools\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
